1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION directing the establishment of the Automatic
2 Expungement Task Force.
3 WHEREAS, having a past conviction can make people ineligible for job
4 opportunities, professional licenses, housing assistance, education, volunteering with
5 their children’s activities, and more; and
6 WHEREAS, expungement lowers rates of recidivism by offering people a clean
7 slate and the opportunity to move forward as full members of their communities; and
8 WHEREAS, over one million adults in Kentucky have a criminal record; and
9 WHEREAS, as many as 44 percent of those adults may be eligible to have their
10 record fully expunged; and
11 WHEREAS, the current process for clearing eligible records can be confusing,
12 expensive, and full of red tape; and
13 WHEREAS, people should not be defined by their records and should have the
14 opportunity to contribute to their community, to work, to get an education, and to achieve
15 their full potential; and
16 WHEREAS, it is time to ensure that a fair shot at redemption is available to all;
17 NOW, THEREFORE,
18 Be it resolved by the Senate of the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of
19 Kentucky, the House of Representatives concurring therein:
20 Section 1. The Legislative Research Commission shall establish the Automatic
21 Expungement Task Force. The task force shall review, study, and make
22 recommendations regarding the development and implementation of electronic processes
23 and procedures for the automatic expungement of records. The task force shall identify
24 and address challenges that may arise during implementation to ensure an effective and
25 efficient system. The task force shall investigate necessary systemic changes,
26 technological requirements, cost estimates, and potential funding sources.
27 Section 2. The Automatic Expungement Task Force shall be composed of the
